  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What drawing techniques should beginners know?",
  "response": "Beginners should focus on a range of fundamental drawing techniques to develop their skills. Here are some essential techniques to start with:\n\n1. **Line Drawing**: Mastering basic lines, such as straight, curved, horizontal, vertical, and diagonal lines, is crucial. Practice controlling the weight and pressure of your lines to create variation.\n\n2. **Hatching and Cross-Hatching**: These techniques involve drawing parallel lines to create shading and texture. Cross-hatching adds another layer of lines in the opposite direction, increasing the depth of shading.\n\n3. **Stippling**: This technique uses small dots to build up texture and value. The density of the dots determines the darkness of the area.\n\n4. **Contour Drawing**: Focus on capturing the outline and main features of a subject. This helps improve observation skills and hand-eye coordination.\n\n5. **Gestural Drawing**: Quick, loose sketches that capture the action or basic form of a subject. This is especially useful for figure drawing and understanding movement.\n\n6. **Blind Contour Drawing**: Draw the outline of an object without looking at your paper. This exercise enhances observation and hand coordination.\n\n7. **Scribbling**: Use loose, circular or random lines to build up form and value quickly. This technique is great for capturing texture and dynamic movement.\n\n8. **Perspective Drawing**: Understanding one-point, two-point, and three-point perspective helps in creating realistic spatial relationships and depth.\n\n9. **Negative Space Drawing**: Focus on the shapes and spaces around and between objects. This aids in accurate proportion and alignment.\n\n10. **Shading and Blending**: Learning how to create gradients through smooth transitions from light to dark using tools like blending stumps or your fingers.\n\n11. **Value Scale**: Practice creating a range of tones from light to dark. This is essential for understanding light, shadow, and contrast.\n\n12. **Still Life Drawing**: Practice drawing from real life objects to improve observation skills, composition, and understanding of light and shadow.\n\nBy practicing these techniques, beginners can build a strong foundation in drawing and gradually progress to more complex subjects and styles.",
